issue.title: make the URL used for the "Open shared document" configurable during the call

labels.name: feature-request
labels.description: Issue which suggest an idea, enhancement or feature to implement

issue.body:
<!--
Thank you for suggesting an idea to make Jitsi Meet better.

Please fill in as much of the template below as you're able.

Note that the ultimate decision for implementing features lies on the Jitsi team, not all feature requests shall be accepted.
-->

**Is your feature request related to a problem you are facing?**
When using shared documents in jitsi it's afaik only possible to configure a base url:

https://jitsi.github.io/handbook/docs/dev-guide/dev-guide-configuration/#etherpad_base

however I'd like to point to specific, diverse shared documents, maybe even hosted on different servers|URLs.

so, if you already have prepared a shared document in advance and are just a jitsi user, it would be nice to be able to set a deep link, e.g. etherpad.example.com/my-topic for the "my-topic" call, instead of the general "etherpad.example.com" base URL which only opens a new clean etherpad.

I at least couldn't find how to achieve this or find an already existing issue for this.

Thanks for the great software, btw :slightly_smiling_face:

issue.title: [iOS] [AudioMode] Cannot route audio output from one bluetooth device to other.
issue.body:
<!--

This issue tracker is only for reporting bugs and tracking issues related to the source code.

Before posting, please make sure to check if the same or similar bugs have already been discussed: https://github.com/jitsi/jitsi-meet/issues

General questions regarding usage, installation, etc. should be posted at https://community.jitsi.org. They will be closed if posted here.

-->

### Description:

When multiple bluetooth devices are connected, only the last connected bluetooth shall have audio output routed to it, even if you select the previous / other bluetooth device(s).

The same issue apparently exists on [iOS itself as asked here](https://developer.apple.com/forums/thread/62954).

### Steps to reproduce:

1. Open Jitsi Mobile App from your iPhone
2. Join any meeting, preferably one hosted at Laptop with their mic unmuted so you can test this.
3. Connect Bluetooth Device 'A', such as AirPods. The iPhone shall automatically route audio output to it.
4. Now, once verified that you can hear audio output on Device 'A', now connect Device 'B', let's say Sony MX4 Pods. The iPhone shall automatically route audio output to the newly connected Device 'B'.
5. Now, from the mobile app, on top right; tap on the 'Speaker' icon which opens Audio Device Selection prompt / bottom sheet.
6. Select Device 'A' from here.

### Expected behavior:

Audio should have been routed to the Device 'A'

### Actual behavior:

Audio remains routed to Device 'B', the last connected Bluetooth device.

### Server information:

[https://meet.jit.si]

### Client information:

- Browser / app version: 22.2.0 build 1652454796
- Operating System: iPhone 11, iOS 14.6

### Additional information:

Unsure if the same happens on Android or not, haven't tested it.

I tried debugging to see if AVAudioSession setPrefferedInput is returning false, but apparently it's also successful. However, just AFTER it if you log AVAudioSession currentRoute, it's still the last connected bluetooth device. I've tried changing categories, mode, setActive, etc, and their orders, to no avail, the same as the referred link about iOS issue on description.

Thank you for your pull request. Please provide a thorough description below.

Contributors guide: https://github.com/jitsi/jitsi-meet/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md
-->
Revert @thttg's changes (#12104) to follow [Microsoft's Localization style guide](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/globalization/localization/ministyleguides/mini-style-guide-trad-chinese#6-spacing) and terminology, spacing specifically.

comment.body:
#12104 removes all the spacing between Chinese and English characters, which [reduces readability](https://github.com/vinta/pangu.js).

> 6. Spacing
Spacing is an important consideration when localizing strings into Traditional Chinese.
> The following general rules are applied:
> Half-width space is needed between Chinese characters and English letters or numbers.
> Half-width space is needed between Chinese characters and half-width punctuation marks: ( ), [ ]. Exception: This rule does not apply to : ; ! ?
> No space is needed around Chinese full-width punctuation marks.

Copied from [Microsoft's Localization style guide](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/globalization/localization/ministyleguides/mini-style-guide-trad-chinese#6-spacing).

@thttg also reuses terms from zhCN, For example, in line 462, 令牌 should be 權杖, and in line 676, 本地 should be 本機.
